# v5.11.x retro — cleanup minor + 9-sibling foldin + heap-map refactor

[[entries]]
name = "v511x_cycle_retro_through_20"
description = "v5.11.x retrospective slots .0-.20: stdlib annotation arc (7 phases), 9-sibling foldin cascade, comment-condensation principle, per-repo isolation Part 1, kybernet 2-part bundle with audit-driven honest split (Part A.ii spawned its own slot when the reporter's 'single source-line edit' framing didn't survive empirical heap-map audit), bote streaming arc 3→1 collapse, RFC 6455 §4.1 fix-with-trivial-LOC. Plus the slot map consolidation pattern (closing OPEN buffer-band gaps when emergent runway opens up)."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["retrospective", "agent", "v5.11.x", "kybernet", "heap-map", "annotation-arc", "snapshot-ping-pong", "bote", "ws-handshake", "rfc-6455", "consolidation"]
content = """
v5.11.x is the **cleanup minor that revealed how much
non-cleanup work was still queued**. Framed at v5.11.0 as
"TS test harness + held-forward absorber", expanded
mid-cycle as consumer-filings (kybernet × 2, bote × 4,
agnos × 2, ai-hwaccel × 1, daimon × 1) plus the
foldin-cascade closed the longest issue queue in the
project's history.

ARC: STDLIB ANNOTATION (.1-.7)

Seven phases of `: i64` / `: Str` / `: Result` return-type
annotations across native lib/ + per-arch syscall peers
+ compiler internals. User pin at v5.11.0 ship: "STDLIB
ANNOTATION FIRST MF EERYTHING ELSE AFTER ALL THAT IS
DONE" — non-negotiable arc ordering. Annotation arc closed
clean across 7 slots; mabda 747-fn out-of-band pass
happened in parallel on the v3 branch (release-blocked
until 3.0.0 GA — counted as project state, not slot
deliverable).

ARC: 9-SIBLING FOLDIN CASCADE (.5)

vani/patra/agnosys/sandhi/sakshi/sigil/yukti/sankoch/niyama
all released at v5.11.5; foldin happened as a single
slot via the sandhi pattern (dist/X.cyr → lib/X.cyr
byte-identical copy). Required `.cyrius-toolchain`
retirement + CI version-pin rewrites across the
ecosystem — that pattern is now `[package].cyrius` in
cyrius.cyml as single source of version truth.

ARC: PER-REPO ISOLATION (.17, .24, .25 pinned)

v5.11.17 shipped Part 1 — `cbt/deps.cyr::_dep_find_stdlib_dir()`
rewritten: dev-mode-first (./lib when src/main.cyr exists)
then cyrius.cyml-pinned (~/.cyrius/versions/<v>/lib),
then legacy global ~/.cyrius/lib fallback. Pinned-but-
not-installed = hard error. Closes the snapshot-ping-
pong wipe wedge that bit twice in v5.11.x (.3, .13).
Parts 2 (CLI version-resolved dispatcher) + 3 (cyriusly
use --global flag) split off to .24/.25 — original
5-item acceptance bar was 3 distinct architectural
pieces, user direction "Reframe — split into 3 slots".

ARC: KYBERNET BUNDLE (.18-.19)

The audit-driven honest split that defined the cycle's
discipline shift. Reporter (kybernet 1.1.5) framed both
cap raises (fn_table 4096→8192 + identifier buffer
131072→262144) as "single source-line edit in cc5".
Audit at .18 entry showed:

- Identifier buffer raise IS mechanical (~10 literals;
  uses existing gap; no shift)
- fn_table raise is a **heap-map refactor**: 15+ fn_*
  tables across scattered locations need relocate-and-
  shift, ~85 hex-literal edits across 15 src/ files

User direction at .18 entry: "Split honestly — ship .18
partial." Honest scope shrink, NOT lazy defer — Part
A.ii (fn_table) got its OWN slot at .19 with full
acceptance bar in the same edit (per
`feedback_deferral_requires_roadmap_pinnage`).

v5.11.19 EXECUTION — five-phase byte-identical heap
refactor:

1. Relocate 7 scattered fn_* tables (fn_deprecated_msg
   0x104000→0x100000, fn_name_hash 0x10C000→0x110000,
   fn_start_hash 0x110000→0x114000, fn_regalloc
   0x1C8000→0x14A000, fn_ret_sid 0x1EC000→0x15A000,
   fn_variadic 0x1F4000→0x16A000, fn_flags 0x1FC000→
   0x17A000) into the 0x100000-0x118000 + 0x14A000-
   0x18A000 free gaps.
2. Shift IR + fixup regions +0x80000 (ir_nodes/blocks/
   state/edges/cp/fixup_tbl/brk-fixup-end) to free
   0x12CA000-0x134A000 for primary block migration.
3. Move primary fn_* block 0x128A000 → 0x12CA000 +
   double stride 0x8000→0x10000.
4. Double extended fn_* block stride at 0x124A000
   (REVERSE-ORDER sed pass to avoid replacement
   collision between adjacent tables — table N's old
   offset is table N-1's new offset).
5. REGFN cap check 4096 → 8192 + warning thresholds +
   error message literals.

cc5 byte-identical at every phase; final size 804,456 B
(was 804,464 B pre-refactor; -8 from string-literal
deltas). 5 phases of self-host fixpoint validation
caught:

- Phase 1 initial misplacement: tables at 0xA0000-
  0xF0000 INSIDE input_buf (0x0-0x100000). First compile
  succeeded (old cc5 unaware of the layout). Second
  compile HUNG — input writes corrupted the relocated
  fn_* tables. Caught at fixpoint check, NOT in ship.
  Real-gap re-placement clean.

Hash tables (fn_name_hash + fn_start_hash) kept at 8192
slots × 2B (mask 8191) — the available gap (369KB
across both sub-bands) couldn't fit 7 doubled tables PLUS
doubled hash tables (384 KB needed). Load factor degrades
to 1.0 at the 8192-fn cap extreme; kybernet's worst-case
3779 fns puts load factor at 0.46 — well below probe
cliff. Documented trade-off.

CHAPTER: BOTE STREAMING ARC (.13-.16)

Four bote consumer filings (.13 sock_set_recv_timeout, .14
arena lifecycle, .15 streaming dispatch primitives, .16 WS
handshake). The .15 slot was originally a 3-slot arc
(MPSC channel + cancellation + per-frame arena); premise
check showed cyrius already had `chan_*` + `atomic_*` (since
v5.5.31) + `arena_*` (since v5.5.x + v5.11.14 `arena_free`)
— actual work was 4 thin shims (`chan_try_recv`, 3 cancel
tokens). 3-slot arc collapsed to 1 slot. .16 WS handshake
was a 5-line fix (RFC 6455 §4.1 key-length check) — proves
the "trivial-LOC fix that gates a real consumer bug" slot
shape is valid when the bug is well-scoped.

The .16 ship ALSO consolidated the slot map: the 2 OPEN
slots freed by .15's arc collapse got assigned to bote WS
handshake (.18 → .16) + the existing pinned slots shifted
back 2 to close the gap. User direction: "close up open gap,
so we have additional runway later." Net: gained 2 OPEN slots
at back of cycle.

KEY PATTERNS THAT RECURRED

**1. Audit-driven honest split.** v5.11.18 → .19 split.
The reporter's framing was wrong; the audit replaced it
with actual scope. Per
`feedback_consumer_request_full_surface`, full surface is
required — but only as defined by the audit, not the
filing. The split is HONEST when the audit-derived scope
genuinely doesn't fit; LAZY when the agent has time and
chose not to. Audit data distinguishes the two.

**2. Trivial-LOC fix that closes a real consumer bug.**
v5.11.16 (WS handshake): 5 lines of code, but those 5
lines close RFC 6455 §4.1 non-conformance that bote
filed. Don't confuse small-diff with low-value — bug
scope is the metric.

**3. Premise-check that finds work already done.**
v5.11.15 — bote filed a 3-slot streaming-primitives arc;
premise check showed 80% of it shipped 2 minors ago.
The slot's value was the thin shims + DISCOVERY for the
consumer (doc block at top of `lib/async.cyr` showing the
intended bote integration pattern, so future consumers
don't re-file the same arc).

**4. Comment-condensation principle.** User pin at .7:
"primary info and changelog pointer, shouldn't HOG
space". The pattern is `# WHY-invariant. See CHANGELOG
[X.Y.Z]` — keep durable rationale in source, move
historical narrative to CHANGELOG. Applied across 8
native lib files at .7 close.

**5. Close-to-archive issue filings.** User pin at .12:
"if issue persists it will get dug out". At slot close,
`git mv` resolved issues → `docs/development/issues/
archived/`. Active queue stays scannable; re-opens are
a `git mv` back. Applied to the cycle's filings
consistently from .12 onward.

**6. Slot map consolidation as a real activity.**
v5.11.16: OPEN slots in front of cycle ≠ fixed positions.
When arc collapse frees runway (the v5.11.15 streaming
arc 3→1), shift pinned items forward to close the gap.
The buffer band moves back, not the pin order. User
direction "close up open gap, so we have additional
runway later" formalizes the move.

**7. The byte-identical-at-every-phase discipline.** The
v5.11.19 heap-map refactor (highest-risk slot in v5.11.x)
ran 5 phases — cc5 byte-identical fixpoint after EACH
phase. Without that discipline, the Phase 1 input_buf
misplacement would have shipped silent. The fixpoint
check is the safety net that pays for slow-and-careful
slot execution on heap-state changes.

THE CYCLE'S META-LESSON: the "cleanup minor" framing was
real but undersized. Cleanup work tends to surface
emergent fixes (kybernet, bote, agnos, ai-hwaccel,
daimon) because the deeper view exposes more consumer
gaps. The right move is to expand the buffer band, not
compress the cleanup work into too few slots. v5.11.x
cycle expanded from .15 close-out to .40 close-out
mid-cycle — that decision is the cycle's procedural win.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "v511x_cycle_retro_21_to_28"
description = "v5.11.x slots .21-.28: per-repo isolation arc closeout (Parts 2+3), PE plumbing + path-API widening fix, #derive accessors >16-field cap, aarch64-native build path latent-since-v5.5.16 surfacing, bote parser quirk closed no-repro with diagnostic improvement"
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["retrospective", "agent", "v5.11.x", "per-repo-isolation", "aarch64-native", "PE-widening", "parser-diagnostic", "premise-check", "gate-gap"]
content = """
v5.11.x continued through the back half (.21-.28) with
the per-repo isolation arc closing, two more PE/Win64
fixes, the agnos accessors-cap raise, and two slots
where premise-check at slot entry rewrote the slot scope
mid-flight (v5.11.27 + v5.11.28).

ARC CLOSEOUT: PER-REPO ISOLATION (.25 + .26)

Part 2 (v5.11.25) — `cyrius` CLI version-resolved dispatcher.
Every `cyrius <cmd>` invocation now reads `cyrius.cyml`'s
`[package].cyrius` field, compares against the binary's
compile-time-embedded `_VERSION_TOOLCHAIN`, and `sys_execve`
re-execs to `~/.cyrius/versions/<pin>/bin/cyrius` if they
differ, with `CYRIUS_RESOLVED=1` env loop guard. Pinned-
but-not-installed = hard error matching v5.11.17 deps
policy. NEW `_VERSION_TOOLCHAIN` literal in
`src/version_str.cyr` (version-bump.sh regen writes it
going forward).

Part 3 (v5.11.26) — `cyriusly use --global` flag. `cyriusly
use 5.11.X` (no flag) now writes `cyrius.cyml`'s
`[package].cyrius` field; `--global` keeps the legacy
`~/.cyrius/current` global-pointer write. Sibling agents
flipping the global pointer for their own tests stopped
affecting other repos.

Together: the snapshot-ping-pong wipe vector closed
end-to-end. v5.11.17 closed the deps stdlib_dir resolution
leg, v5.11.25 closed the CLI dispatch leg, v5.11.26
closed the operator-error leg (`cyriusly use 5.10.x`
without `--global` no longer trips other repos).

CHAPTER: PE/WIN64 PATH-API SURFACE (.21-.23)

v5.11.21 (PE plumbing premise debunk) — ai-hwaccel filed
"cc5_win broken on cass" with `syscall(60, 42)` exit; cass
verify showed `exit=42` clean (the bug was the Win
`%ERRORLEVEL%` parse-time-expansion gotcha from the
v5.10.49 incident — `cmd /c "prog & echo %errorlevel%"`
falsely reports 0; needs `cmd /v /c "... !errorlevel!"`).
Real gap was unrouted syscalls 83/87/89 (mkdir, unlink,
rmdir). v5.11.21 added CreateDirectoryW/DeleteFileW
auto-import + parser dispatch with -ENOSYS placeholder
bodies.

v5.11.23 (UTF-16 widening fix) — surfaced once the new
path-API kernel32 calls actually ran on Win11 26200 (cass):
`ntdll!+0x41912` fault in path-validation. Wine accepted
both shapes; native Win11 didn't. The fault was in
`_pe_widen_utf8_to_utf16` for a specific input shape that
exit42/hello-world never exercised. Fixed in
`src/backend/x86/emit.cyr`. Added PE-mode gate to
`programs/check.cyr` exercising CreateFileW +
CreateDirectoryW on cass — same gate-gap pattern as the
v5.11.27 aarch64-native discovery (cross-arch CI gap is
the bug-incubator).

SLOT: AGNOS ACCESSORS >16-FIELD (.24)

agnos 1.28.3 `struct Process` (22 fields) hit a no-bounds-
check overflow in `src/frontend/lex_pp.cyr` per-struct
`field_names` / `field_types` / `offsets` tables (hard-
sized at 16 entries). The 17th field overflowed into
`field_types[0]`, offsets diverged silently, agnos's CR3
field corrupted on first context switch → kernel
page-fault. Raised cap + added hard-cap diagnostic. Silent
miscompile that broke a kernel — exactly the surface
class the agnos arc surfaces.

SLOT: AARCH64-NATIVE BUILD REPAIR (.27 — RE-PINNED MID-SLOT)

v5.11.27 was originally pinned as the bote parser quirk
slot. At slot entry, the premise-check pin fired: `ssh pi
to verify aarch64 native`. Pi-side compile of a freshly
cross-built `cc5-native-aarch64` SIGILL'd at first
`alloc()`. Two stacked stale-fork bugs surfaced, both
latent since the v5.5.16 main_*.cyr per-arch split (six
minors, ~150 patches without a real-hardware aarch64-
native end-to-end):

(1) `src/main_aarch64_native.cyr` was missing the
`CYRIUS_MACHO_ARM` env-driven `CYRIUS_TARGET_LINUX`/MACOS
predefine block that `main_aarch64.cyr` shipped at v5.5.16
— so every `#ifdef CYRIUS_TARGET_LINUX` in lib/ was dead
under native build and alloc/vec_* undefined.

(2) `_init_cyrius_lib` + `_check_shadow_lib` in lex.cyr
used bare `syscall(2, path, …)`; aarch64's xlat changes
2→56 (openat) but does NOT reshuffle args, so the path
landed in the dfd slot and openat got EFAULT.
`_cyrius_lib_len` stayed 0, version-pinned-lib fallback
dead.

Per the no-unilateral-scope-decisions pin, mid-slot
re-scoping needs explicit user direction — used
AskUserQuestion to ask whether to ship the aarch64 repair
or continue with the parser quirk. User answered "Native-
aarch64 bugs first; quirk slips". Roadmap updated
in-edit, parser quirk slipped to v5.11.28.

Pi e2e verified: alloc + vec_push + vec_get + assert +
assert_summary program ran from both cwd-with-lib AND
cwd-without-lib (proving the version-pinned-lib fallback
fires correctly), exit=0, "1 passed, 0 failed".

Latency narrative: same shape as v5.11.23's Win64
RSP-alignment 6-minor latency. Cross-arch CI gap is the
incubator. v5.11.37 (cc5_aarch64_native cross-bin ship)
is the slot pinned to add pi-side CI smoke and close the
gate-gap permanently.

SLOT: BOTE PARSER QUIRK — CLOSED NO-REPRO (.28)

bote 2.7.1's `expected ')', got string` filing
(intermittent, path-dependent, on
`assert(streq(call(args,n), "lit") == 1, "msg")`).
Premise-check at slot entry: reverted bote's `cap0/cap1`
var-stage workaround to recreate the inline-nested shape,
compiled at v5.11.27 AND v5.10.34 (filing version, intact
in `~/.cyrius/versions/5.10.34/bin/cc5`) — clean parse
both times. Synthetic fuzz 0/28 across 9 preceding-line
counts × both versions and 10 ident counts spanning the
filing's ~8700 boundary speculation.

User pin "Hunt harder for the path-dependent trigger"
required pushing past the easy "no repro, close issue"
read. The hunt evidence: filing version + current both
clean, identifier-fuzz boundary-spanning fuzz clean,
no synthetic context that triggers. The likely-fix
commit was `f3e98a3e` (first in v5.11.18, doubled ident
buffer 131072 → 262144 bytes) — lines up with the
filing's Speculation 2 hash-collision boundary, but
unprovable without a repro.

Ships: regression test (13 asserts locking the shape) +
diagnostic improvement (hint line in `ERR_EXPECT` when
`expected ')'/','` AND got-token is string, gesturing
at "stage inner call into `var`" — saves consumers from
the misleading-fix rabbit hole the filing called out).

KEY PATTERNS THAT RECURRED IN .21-.28

**1. Premise-check at slot entry rewriting scope.**
v5.11.27 was the cleanest example: routine ssh verify
exposed bugs bigger than the original filing, and
mid-flight scope change required explicit user direction
rather than silent re-scoping. The pin enforced the
asking; the answer ("Native-aarch64 bugs first; quirk
slips") got pinned to roadmap in the same edit per the
deferral-requires-pinnage rule.

**2. Hunt-harder when no-repro looks easy.** v5.11.28 —
default-mode "no repro at filing version, close issue"
was the obvious shape; user pin "Hunt harder" forced
the synthetic fuzz across preceding-line + ident-count
gradients. Net result was the same close-no-repro
outcome, but earned through evidence. The diagnostic
improvement that landed is the value layer that survives
even when the underlying bug is unreproducible.

**3. Cross-arch CI gap as bug-incubator.** Both v5.11.23
(Win64 RSP) and v5.11.27 (aarch64-native) followed the
same pattern: x86 host compile clean, real-target run
fails. Pi/cass/ecb cross-test gates close after the
fact, not before. v5.11.37 closes the aarch64-native
leg; PE-mode check.cyr gate closed the Win path-API
leg at v5.11.23.

**4. Misleading-diagnostic earns its own slot share.**
The bote filing's underlying bug is intermittent and
unreproducible at v5.11.28, but the misleading
`expected ')', got string` symptom remained a real
consumer-time-sink. One hint string saves future-bisect
time for any parse failure of this shape, whether the
state-leak is still live or not. Layer 2 of the filing
was always the higher-leverage half.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "v511x_cycle_retro_29_to_49"
description = "v5.11.x slots .29-.49: kernel ELF emitter section-header fixes for GRUB (.29-.31), user-binary ELF section-header parity sweep (.32-.34), parser-to-emit named-op refactor arc Classes B/C/D + drift gate (.35-.39), f64_abs peephole (.40), CVE-08 cld hardening + doc cleanup (.41), LSP semanticTokens locals+params (.42), EMITELF64_KERNEL + multiboot2 + EFI64-entry tag for Path A (.43), build/cc5 mabda-contamination postmortem + LSP argv[0] self-resolution (.44), P(-1) hardening 4-bundle (.45), FIXUP↔EMITELF64_KERNEL entry-arithmetic agreement (.46), gnoboot UEFI Application emit 3-slot arc with same-day filing-to-OVMF-boot turnaround (.47-.49)."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["retrospective", "agent", "v5.11.x", "back-half", "elf-section-headers", "named-op-refactor", "drift-gate", "elf64-kernel", "multiboot2", "uefi", "efi-application", "gnoboot", "ovmf", "agnos-path-c", "premise-check"]
content = """
v5.11.x back half (.29-.49) turned the "cleanup minor"
framing on its head: the kernel/boot path work that
opens AGNOS pulled the cycle into platform-capability
territory. Two parallel arcs ran across the back half:
the **ELF-section-header parity sweep** (kernel emit
catching up to user-bin emit on GRUB compatibility),
and the **gnoboot UEFI Application emit arc** (the
sovereign-bootloader unblocker that ships at v5.11.49).
Path A (ELF64 multiboot2 via GRUB) died on iron at .46
due to a GRUB-internal W^X bug; Path C (sovereign UEFI
bootloader, no GRUB) became the live MVP boot path.

ARC: ELF SECTION-HEADER PARITY (.29-.34)

v5.11.29 added a minimal section-header table to the
kernel ELF emitter so GRUB's `grub_elf32_get_shnum`
accepts the binary. v5.11.30 (aarch64 kernel ELF),
.31 (`cyrld` user-binary linker), .32 (x86 user-binary
EMITELF_USER), .33 (PP_IFDEF_PASS 2 MB → 8 MB cap), .34
(aarch64 user-binary EMITELF_USER) closed the parity
sweep across all five ELF emitters in the toolchain.
Same shape repeating across files = candidate for
parser-to-emit named-op consolidation, which is exactly
what the next arc tackled.

ARC: PARSER-TO-EMIT NAMED-OP REFACTOR + DRIFT GATE (.35-.39)

Four classes of parser → backend emit direct-byte calls
audited and migrated to named-op helper fns per
backend. **Class B** (.36): PIC-vs-direct address loads
— EMIT_LEA_ABS / EMIT_MOVI_ABS. **Class C** (.37): f64
unary ops — EF64_NEG / EF64_FROM / EF64_TO / etc., 8
new named ops per backend. **Class D** (.35): aligned-
to-the-v5.7.12 audit doc. **Drift gate** (.39): new
`_parse_emit_drift_gate()` in `programs/check.cyr`
scans `parse_*.cyr` for any `EB(S, 0xXX)` shape and
fails if found — locks the refactor in. ESWITCH_DISPATCH_*
family closed Class B's missed-site list. The drift
gate is the cycle's most consequential procedural win:
locks in a refactor pattern that would have rotted
back through future changes.

ARC: KERNEL ELF64 + MULTIBOOT2 + EFI64-ENTRY (.43-.46)

The AGNOS Path A unlock attempt. v5.11.43 shipped
`EMITELF64_KERNEL` — gated by `CYRIUS_ELF64_KERNEL=1`
env var setting `_TARGET_ELF64_KERNEL` x86 flag at
`src/main.cyr:1003`. New emitter writes ELF64 header
(64 B) + 1 PT_LOAD program header (56 B) + multiboot2
header (48 B) at file offset 0 → entry at file offset
168 → e_entry = 0x1000A8.

v5.11.44 caught a P0: `build/cc5` had been committed
as a 1.39 MB binary containing mabda/wgpu/compute-pipeline
strings (NOT the cyrius compiler — clobbered by some
build-script slip cp'ing another binary). `git diff
aad19f6a -- src/ lib/` was empty; current src self-hosts
to the canonical 821,712 B. Same shape silently
recurred at v5.11.28/.29 (fixed at .30). v5.11.45 added
the build/cc5 contamination grep gate (greps for
'mabda: gpu' / 'wgpuDevice' / 'compute_pipeline') to
fail-fast next time.

v5.11.46 was the agnos-filed bug fix: FIXUP's
`kmode == 1` branch hard-coded `entry = 0x100060`
(legacy ELF32+multiboot1 layout), while EMITELF64_KERNEL
placed code at `0x1000A8` (ELF64+multiboot2 layout).
0x48 = 72-byte mismatch shifted every absolute fixup
72 B earlier; `mov rcx, 0x1001D8` landed inside the
multiboot2 header instead of `.rodata`. Fixed at
`src/backend/x86/fixup.cyr:95` by gating the entry
value on `_TARGET_ELF64_KERNEL`. New
`_elf64_kernel_entry_gate()` regression-floors the
agreement: compiles `kernel_hello.cyr`, locates the
"Hello from Cyrius!" string's true VA, asserts the
OLD-entry-shifted VA (`true_va - 0x48`) is absent.

The agnos-side filing came through the proper channel
(filed in cyrius/docs/development/issues/ — not as a
drive-by patch) per the v5.11.45 incident: an
agnosticos agent had directly patched
`src/backend/x86/fixup.cyr` with a technically-correct
fix while working on AGNOS boot. Project leader pinned
"EVEN IF ITS 100% CORRECT THE VIOLATION IS THE PROBLEM
... FIRABLE OFFENCE IN REAL LIFE IS MY ISSUE." Patch
reverted; bug filed as proper issue; cyrius-side slot
implements on its own slot lifecycle (premise check
→ fix → cross-arch verify → gate → CHANGELOG).

ARC: GNOBOOT UEFI APPLICATION EMIT (.47-.49)

After v5.11.46 unblocked Path A from the cyrius side,
the agnos boot agent discovered Path A was dead-on-iron
anyway: GRUB's `grub_relocator64_efi_boot` writes
kernel register state directly into its own RO `.text`
(the `grub_relocator64_efi_start` stub's embedded
register-state immediates at .text 0x8AA-0x8F7).
Modern UEFI firmware (OVMF 2024+ confirmed) enforces
the UEFI Memory Attributes Protocol RO bit on code
pages; the writes fault. **GRUB itself is the
blocker** — not cyrius, not the kernel. Resolution =
Path C: sovereign UEFI bootloader (`gnoboot`, ~2000
LoC of Cyrius), no GRUB on the boot path.

Path C blocked on cyrius emitting UEFI Application
PE32+ binaries — subsystem 0xA, no kernel32 imports,
populated .reloc, MS x64 ABI (UEFI uses the same as
Windows PE). Filing came through proper channel.
Premise audit at .47 entry found the filing's
speculation about `.reloc` + DllCharacteristics work
was partially stale: `.reloc` + IMAGE_REL_BASED_DIR64
shipped v5.5.35; DllCharacteristics 0x0160 (NX_COMPAT
+ DYNAMIC_BASE + HIGH_ENTROPY_VA) shipped v5.6.31
probe. Actual compiler deltas were narrow.

**v5.11.47** — `_TARGET_EFI_APPLICATION` flag declared
in all 3 backend `emit.cyr` files (x86 real, aarch64+cx
stubs); env var `CYRIUS_TARGET_EFI=1` in main.cyr +
main_win.cyr flips both `_TARGET_PE = 1` (EFI implies
PE container) and the EFI flag. Subsystem branch 3 →
10 in `pe/emit.cyr:746`. EEXIT EFI variant in
`x86/emit.cyr:545` — single `0xC3` (ret), firmware
reads rax as EFI_STATUS. ExitProcess import skip at
`_pe_layout:439`. Data Dirs [1]/[12] zeroed (no
kernel32 in UEFI). REFACTOR SQUEEZE-IN: 9
near-identical `_pe_ensure_<X>(S)` / `_pe_<X>_get()`
pairs consolidated to a single `_pe_register_kernel32`
helper — single point for the import-time EFI guard
(fail-fast if any kernel32 reroute fires under EFI).

**v5.11.48** — `programs/efi_probe.cyr`: 64 LoC,
single-asm-block, no fixups, walks SystemTable →
ConOut → OutputString. Premise discovery: cyrius PE
entry prologue is `e9 00 00 00 00` (5-byte `jmp +0`)
— touches no GPRs, so firmware-supplied RCX
(ImageHandle) and RDX (SystemTable) survive into the
first user byte. Verified by 4-NOP marker landing at
`.text + 0x05`. Made inline-asm-first the right
capture shape; fn calls would clobber RCX/RDX with
arg-setup `mov`s before user code sees them. New
`_efi_emit_gate()` asserts MZ+PE+Magic+Subsystem 0xA
+ NX_COMPAT + Data Dirs zeroed + .text has ret.
Compiler nudge: DllCharacteristics force NX_COMPAT
when EFI mode + zero fixups (the v5.6.31 logic only
set it when `_pe_reloc_vsize != 0`).

**v5.11.49** — Manual OVMF smoke of .48 output:
`BdsDxe: failed to load ... Not Found`. Walk-through:
DOS+PE+Subsystem+DllChar+DataDirs all correct, but
COFF Characteristics = 0x0023 includes **RELOCS_STRIPPED**
(0x0001). OVMF firmware treats it as "load at exact
ImageBase=0x140000000 or fail" — runtime services
occupy nearby pages, allocation fails, BdsDxe reports
"Not Found." Fix at `pe/emit.cyr:714`: EFI mode clears
RELOCS_STRIPPED unconditionally. Post-fix:
`BdsDxe: starting Boot0002 ... hello, uefi ...
BdsDxe: loading Boot0000 BootManagerMenuApp` — full
round-trip working. New `_efi_ovmf_smoke_gate()`
runtime-floors the result: builds GPT disk + ESP +
boots qemu+OVMF with -serial stdio + greps for
"hello, uefi"; SKIP gracefully if tooling absent.

Filing → ship: **same day**. Morning filing
(2026-05-13) → afternoon arc closed + runtime-verified.
The filing estimated "150-300 LoC + new probe + verify
floor"; actual was ~250 LoC across .47/.48/.49
including the refactor squeeze-in. Premise audit saved
scope by finding `.reloc` + DllChar + COFF
Characteristics machinery already shipped.

KEY PATTERNS FROM .29-.49

**1. Section-header parity as the missed-half class.**
The .29-.34 arc revealed a recurring shape: an emitter
gets a fix in one of its 5 instantiations (x86 user,
x86 kernel, aarch64 user, aarch64 kernel, cyrld
linker), but the other 4 silently miss it. Five slots
of catch-up was the cost. The named-op refactor that
followed (.35-.39) is the structural answer — same op
encoded once per backend, drift gate prevents
divergence.

**2. RELOCS_STRIPPED is OVMF's silent rejector.** The
v5.11.49 lesson: standard UEFI Application binaries
(rEFInd, systemd-boot, GRUB-EFI) NEVER set
RELOCS_STRIPPED. OVMF firmware treats the bit as a
hard "exact-ImageBase-or-fail" contract; if firmware
can't allocate the requested base, BdsDxe reports
"Not Found" with no indication the bit was the
problem. cyrius's PE backend now clears RELOCS_STRIPPED
unconditionally in EFI mode. Pinned as a gotcha in
field_notes/compiler/gotchas.cyml for future agents.

**3. Same-day filing-to-ship turnaround.** The .47-.49
arc closed in one afternoon because three factors
aligned: (a) the filing arrived through the proper
channel with technical content rich enough to scope
from; (b) cyrius's PE backend had `.reloc` + DllChar
machinery already shipped from years prior; (c)
existing test infrastructure (gate pattern from .46's
ELF64 entry gate, exec_vec_str from process.cyr,
qemu/OVMF/mtools available locally). Mid-cycle
turnaround at this speed isn't repeatable for every
filing, but it is the upper bound when scope + tooling
+ filing-quality all align.

**4. Path A → Path C pivot is a cycle-level lesson.**
Two minors of work on Path A (v5.11.43 EMITELF64_KERNEL,
v5.11.46 FIXUP entry fix) and Path A is still dead
because GRUB itself has a W^X bug under modern UEFI.
Cyrius emit was correct; the consumer's host stack
was broken. Resolution wasn't "fix GRUB" (out of
scope; GRUB is C+autotools+years-of-history) but
"replace GRUB with our own bootloader" — which IS in
scope because gnoboot is ~2000 LoC of cyrius. The
lesson: when an external dep blocks a load-bearing
path AND there's a sovereignty option, the
sovereignty option might be cheaper than fighting
the dep.

**5. Refactor squeeze-in pattern.** The `_pe_ensure_*`
9-fn consolidation at .47 wasn't on the filing's
critical path — it was added because (a) the EFI
import-guard wanted a single source of truth, and
(b) 9 near-duplicates is the closeout-pass refactor
shape CLAUDE.md item #6 names. Both delivered in the
same slot because they compose: the helper IS where
the EFI guard lives. This is the cleanest example
in v5.11.x of the "squeeze-in opportunity" the user
asks me to look for at slot entry.

**6. Process pin (mid-cycle).** The v5.11.45
unauthorized-cross-repo-patch incident wrote a hard
rule into memory: "Cross-repo agents editing cyrius
source is a firable-offence violation — always revert
+ file as issue, never adopt drive-by patches." The
gnoboot arc at .47-.49 is what the proper-channel
shape looks like in practice: agnosticos files a
detailed issue in cyrius/docs/development/issues/,
cyrius-side investigator does premise check + scopes
the work + ships through cyrius's own slot lifecycle.
Same technical content, completely different process
contract.

CYCLE STATS (through v5.11.49)

- 50 slots shipped (.0 - .49); .68/.69 pinned for close
- cc5: 815,432 B (v5.11.0) → 823,112 B (v5.11.49); +7,680 B / +0.94 %
- check.sh: 65 → 72 gates (+7 new across the cycle)
- 1 new stdlib module (n/a — annotation arc + foldins
  were version-bumps of existing modules)
- 1 new sample program (programs/efi_probe.cyr at .48)
- 1 new consumer repo unblocked (gnoboot, MVP boot
  path; cyrius.cyml pinned to `cyrius = "5.11.49"`)
- 3 new field_notes/compiler/gotchas entries from this
  cycle so far (RELOCS_STRIPPED-vs-OVMF, FIXUP-vs-
  EMITELF64_KERNEL entry, PE prologue e9-jmp discovery)

v5.11.x is still in-flight (49 slots through 2026-05-13;
cycle pinned to close at .68 with .69 reserved for
conditional mabda 3.0 fold). The above retro covers
the published back half through .49. A final
v5.11.x_cycle_close entry will land at .68/.69 ship
with the full cycle summary + heap-map reorg + any
mabda-fold ceremony.
"""
